rong>(2011, Universal, 15) would be the films of Shane Meadows, with which this shares both a tough edge and a soft heart. Charlie Creed-Miles stars as the eponymous ex-con whose release from prison is met with dismay by his son, Dean (Will Poulter), who has been acting in loco parentis to younger brother Jimmy (Sammy Williams) for years. Initially, Bill doesn't want anything to do with his children, preferring to head north in search of pastures new. But when social services threaten to put the kids into care, Dean insists that his errant father stick around long enough to tick the paperwork boxes, and an uneasy bond begins to develop between this once broken family.</p><p>Since his first eye-catching appearance in the fabulous <em>Son of Rambow</em>, Poulter has gone from strength to strength and here cements his promise as a charismatic and energetic screen presence; the sparks that fly between him and the excellently raddled Creed-Miles are utterly convincing, suggesting that Fletcher's years working for directors as diverse as Lynch, Jarman and Fernando Trueba have given him a fine affinity with actors. There's a real sense of affection for these characters, married to a disarming narrative sweetness about the way their tangled lives gradually start to form an unbreakable knot.</p><p>Co-writers Fletcher and Danny King are rather less sure-footed on the female roles, leaving the talented Liz White (brilliant in <em>Life on Mars</em>) to wrestle with the caricatured \"tart with a heart\" role of Roxy, of which she gamely makes the most. Not perfect, then, but rewarding and entertaining fare none the less, which suggests a solid future for Fletcher behind as well as in front of the camera. Extras include deleted scenes and fairly solid making-of material.</p><p>There are more crises of childhood innocence in the <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/2012/mar/15/dardenne-brothers-dont-argue-actors\" title=\"\">Dardennes</a>' latest Cannes prize-winner, <strong>The Kid with a Bike</strong> (2011, Artificial Eye, 12), a brilliantly moving and ultimately optimistic account of a young boy struggling to come to terms with his father's abandonment (a recurring theme) who is taken under the wing of a local hairdresser. Seasoned performer Cécile de France and newcomer Thomas Doret are breathtakingly natural as the uneasy pair, each quietly terrified by the search for something permanent and immutable in their disparate lives. As always with these most humanist of film-makers, the small triumphs of the human soul can transcend the bleakest of circumstances, finding joy in the most unexpected places and weaving fairytale magic from the dark matter of unblinking social realism.</p><p>There's absolutely nothing \"real\" about <strong>Act of Valour </strong>(2012, Momentum, 15), a breast-beating orgy of self-aggrandising action in which \"real\" Navy Seals play with \"real\" guns and \"real\" ammo in \"real\" situations, all in the name of fatuous faux authenticity. Listening to co-directors Mike McCoy and Scott Waugh blather on about doing justice to America's military heroes by casting them in their grotty little \"war on terror\" movie you figure they must be taking the piss. But no, this really is <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/movie/125574/tropic.thunder\" title=\"\"><em>Tropic Thunder</em></a> without the jokes – a flatulent, flag-waving headache of a film that insists on screaming loudly about its hard-core \"reality\" while disappearing swiftly up Rambo's wholly fictional butt-hole. Hoo ha, indeed.</p><p>It would take a hard heart not to be tickled by <strong>StreetDance 2</strong> (2012, Entertainment One, PG), the sequel to the British 3D hit in which super-athletic young people perform feats of dancing derring-do against an array of scenic European settings. Last time it was ballet; this time it's salsa, which adds spice to the mix, courtesy of Tom Conti's non-specifically Mediterranean-accented mentor. Hats off to co-directors Max Giwa and Dania Pasquini, who never let the action flag, and whose recent contribution to London 2012 was one of the highlights of the Cultural Olympiad's short film strand.</p><p>There's no doubting Robert Pattinson's commitment to escaping the romantic teen-idol status bestowed upon him by the Twilight series. Before headlining in David Cronenberg's \"aggressively unlikable\" <em>Cosmopolis</em>, he took an equally unlovable role in the ensemble drama <strong>Bel Ami </strong>(2012, StudioCanal, 15), based on Guy de Maupassant's novel about an amoral rake crawling his way up the incestuous social ladder of late 19th-century Paris. Pattinson is in good company, with Kristin Scott Thomas, Uma Thurman, Christina Ricci, Colm Meaney and more all going great guns, visibly inhaling the fetid air of costumed corruption. Shame, then, that the film itself comes across as <em>Dangerous Liaisons</em>-lite despite the down-and-dirty efforts of its impressive players.</p>","headline":"Mark Kermode's DVD round-up","trailText":"An old lag faces up to fatherhood in Dexter Fletcher's entertaining directorial debut, writes <strong>Mark Kermode</strong>","newspaperPageNumber":"26","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Observer","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/7/18/1342611949143/wild-bill-003.jpg","wordcount":"780","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"393263772","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"6433612","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Mark Kermode","newspaperEditionDate":"2012-07-22T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"1775187","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2012-08-10T23:05:00Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2012/jul/22/wild-bill-kid-bike-valour-dvd","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/film/2012/jul/22/wild-bill-kid-bike-valour-dvd","tags":[{"id":"film/series/mark-kermode-dvd-round-up","webTitle":"Mark Kermode'