to suggest a desire to cover real fear rather than mere callousness. Think about it – when was the last time you questioned the \"motivation\" behind a throwaway Bond quip? That fact alone should tell you just how much Mendes has changed the game.</p><p>Playing the razor-sharp foil to Bond's walking (-dead) wounded is Javier Bardem, long recognised as a connoisseur of the scary haircut (witness <em>No Country for Old Men</em>), to which he here adds creepy teeth and metrosexual mama's-boy menace. According to Mendes, most of the villainous Silva's real weirdness came from Bardem himself, who wanted to beef up the character into a real three-dimensional nemesis, an ambition that he achieves with aplomb.</p><p>But at the heart of it all is Judi Dench's steely M, whose role vacillates between deadpan <em>Mommie Dearest</em> and no-nonsense operational stalwart, providing the crucial link between hero and villain that drives the drama. By the time we get to the third act, with its <em>Straw Dogs</em>-siege and <em>Home Alone</em>-style DIY aesthetic, Mendes and co have cut right down to the bone with satisfyingly meaty results. Extras include two commentary tracks, most notably a nonstop analysis from Mendes, who talks enthusiastically and engagingly about a film he clearly loves as much of the rest of us.</p><p>Those in search of more may wish to track down the recently released <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/movie/149557/everything-or-nothing\" title=\"\"><strong>Everything or Nothing: The Untold Story of 007</strong></a> (2012, Fox, 12), a lively romp through Bond history (which always looked like a glorified DVD extra) boasting a surprisingly self-aware Roger Moore, a terrifically entertaining George Lazenby and even a shadowy adversary in the shape of Kevin McClory, whose long-running ownership dispute lured Connery to the double agent dark side for <em>Never Say Never Again</em>, the film that thankfully failed to kill the franchise.</p><p>Woody Allen's non-NY films have often suffered from a tourist board's view of their settings, none more so than <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/movie/149157/to-rome-with-love\" title=\"\"><strong>To Rome With Love</strong></a><strong> </strong>(2012, Sony, 12). As usual, these characters are all travelling first class, living in a world saturated with dappled sunshine and endless leisure time, in which prostitutes look like Penélope Cruz and everyone knows exactly where their next cappuccino is coming from. The four disconnected stories here are variable fare shot through with a (cine) literacy that is less satisfying than <em>Midnight in Paris</em>, less poignant than <em>Stardust Memories</em> and less scabrous than <em>Celebrity</em> (to which the surreal Roberto Benigni section alludes directly). Yet for all its flaws, this still raises plenty of chuckles, if not belly laughs, and Woody's trademark specs are rose-tinted enough to leave the local authorities hungry for more.</p><p>The main problem with <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/movie/146822/savages\" title=\"\"><strong>Savages</strong></a><strong> </strong>(2012, Universal, 18) is that I couldn't care less about its dope-dealing antiheroes and nor, it appears, could Oliver Stone. He's far more interested in Salma Hayek's fearsome dragon lady, John Travolta's compromised lawman and Benicio Del Toro's fiendishly mustachioed thug, all of whom are noticeable by their absence the minute the young leads take centre stage.</p><p>It doesn't help that our narrator, \"O\" (for Ophelia – no, really), has to deliver lines such as: \"I had orgasms, he had war-gasms\" without laughing, but somewhere in the middle of the preachy drug war mess there's a serviceable exploitation movie (the sex, drugs and violence trimmed for cinemas has been reinstated) struggling to get out. Shame about the hippy-dippy baggage.</p>","headline":"Mark Kermode's DVD round-up","trailText":"Sam Mendes breathes welcome new life into the tire