, we have knife-sharp central performances from Jamie Foxx and Christoph Waltz as (respectively) the recently freed titular slave and sharpshooting \"dentist\" Dr King Schultz, on a mission to rescue Django's wife from the slimy clutches of Leonardo DiCaprio's Calvin Candie.</p><p>The real jaw-dropper, however, is a brilliantly counterintuitive turn from Samuel L Jackson as Candie's insanely loyal house-servant, Stephen, a terrifying portrait of head-turned devotion that offers the film's most potentially radical element. It's here that whatever rude \"politics\" this possesses (including the usual fetishisation of the \"N word\") has gnarly bite. Elsewhere, it's more fan-boyish fare, with nods toward such outré sources as Richard Fleischer's <em>Mandingo</em>, a cameo from Franco Nero, and a jukebox soundtrack heavy on dusty Morricone.</p><p>Tarantino's claim that the lip-smacking violence puts the real horror of slavery on screen for the first time is nonsense – it's more an example of the grindhouse schlock in which this revels, and that has long been his stock in trade. There's no doubting his skill as a maestro of visceral cinema, nor the tangible enthusiasm of his cast for savouring his ripe and raw dialogue. If only such vibrancy were matched by an equally powerful controlling force – preferably a strong producer standing over him in the editing room with a very big stick, reminding him of Roger Corman's mantra that very few movies wouldn't benefit from shedding a third of their running time.</p><p>In stark contrast to Tarantino's unruly style, Clint Eastwood stars in (but does not direct) <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/2012/dec/02/trouble-with-the-curve-review\" title=\"\"><strong>Trouble With the Curve</strong></a> (2012, Warner, 12), an old-fashioned tale of hard-bitten father-daughter bonding that is very \"ruly\" indeed. An antithetical companion-piece to <em>Moneyball</em>, this pitches Clint as an ailing baseball scout whose lifetime of on-the-ground experience is in danger of being eclipsed by young guns playing the numbers game. Director Robert Lorenz served as producer and first assistant director on several Eastwood movies and has adopted his mentor's no-fuss style that, combined with the formulaic narrative, makes for unsurprising fare.</p><p>But there's real charm in the chemistry between Clint's post-<em>Gran Torino</em> codger (his wounded-bear growl sounds like Tom Waits with a throat infection) and Amy Adams's long-suffering daughter, whose exasperation with – and affection for – her insufferable father rings through every scene. Justin Timberlake completes the triangle as the former player turned scout whose narrative trajectory is obvious from the outset. No curve balls, then, but down-the-line drama aimed straight at the heart.</p><p>As cheap movie locations go, the inside of a rental minivan must come top of the pile. Full marks, then, to the makers of <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/2013/may/12/vehicle-19-review-paul-walker\" title=\"\"><strong>Vehicle 19</strong></a><strong> </strong>(2013, StudioCanal, 12) for keeping the budget to a minimum as Paul Walker's ill-fated ex-con picks up the wrong hire car and finds himself in possession of a mobile phone, a handgun and a kidnapped woman he must deliver to corrupt South African police officers pronto. It all makes little or no narrative sense and barrels inevitably toward a splendidly silly climax, but it's hard not to admire the stripped-down ethos of Mukunda Michael Dewil's six-pack-and-a-curry actioner that benefits hugely from a lean, mean 85-minute running time.</p><p>\"At the end of the day, all we can do is search for the truth, learn from it and, most importantly, defend it\". Bypassing UK cinemas after a \"bijou\" US opening, the Canadian thriller <strong>A Dark Truth</strong> (2012, Sony, 15) sends Andy Garcia's retired CIA operative turned truth-telling talk-show host to the Ecuadorian jungle to confront the corporate cover-up of a massacre fuelled by money, water, and power. Here he meets Forest Whitaker's eco-warrior who divides his time between delivering equally portentous speeches and dodging bullets in firefights. Writer-director Damian Lee, who picked up a Boston film festival prize for directing this confused sociopolitical romp, similarly juggles his attentions between jaw-jaw and war-war. It's an odd affair, occasionally diverting in its conspiracy intrigues and bursts of scenic adventure, but most charitably viewed as surprisingly starry straight-to-DVD fodder (Deborah Kara Unger, Steven Bauer, Eva Longoria) rather than a rambling, big-screen misfire.</p>","headline":"Mark Kermode's DVD round-up","trailText":"<p>A strong editor could have helped an overly indulged Quentin Tarantino to make a better film, writes Mark Kermode</p>","newspaperPageNumber":"24","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Observer","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Observer/Pix/pictures/2013/5/17/1368814075492/2012-DJANGO-UNCHAINED-005.jpg","wordcount":"709","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"408922960","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"7601826","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Mark Kermode","newspaperEditionDate":"2013-05-19T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"1908107","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2013-06-09T12:01:00Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/may/19/django-unchained-dvd-mark-kermode","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/film/2013/may/19/django-unchained-dvd-mark-kermode","tags":[{"id":"film/series/mark-kermode-dvd-round-up","webTitle":"Mark Kermode's DVD round-up","description":"Mark Kermode reviews the latest DVD releases","type":"series","sectionId":"film","sectionName":"Film","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/series/mark-kermode-dvd-round-up","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/film/series/mark-kermode-dvd-round-up","references":[]},{"id