lgia-for-light-turin-dvd","fields":{"secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Observer/Pix/pictures/2012/9/5/1346853886059/Nostalgia-For-The-Light-K-005.jpg","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3a84v","standfirst":"Nostalgia for the Light; The Pirates! In an Adventure With Scientists!; The Turin Horse; American Pie: Reunion; Goodbye First Love; Safe","hasStoryPackage":"false","lastModified":"2014-05-21T07:30:50Z","body":"<p>Rooted in the earth of Chile's Atacama desert, 10,000 feet above sea level, Patricio Guzmán's spine-tinglingly profound docu-poem <strong>Nostalgia for the Light</strong> (2010, New Wave, 12) explores the dizzyingly diverse efforts of those sifting the sands of the present in search of the past. For astronomers looking out into the ethereal clarity of the sky, Atacama is a haven where the very boundaries of our universe become darkness visible, revealing the origins of our world. For the wives and relatives of \"the disappeared\", those murdered and buried under Pinochet's brutal regime, the fragmentary traces of their loved ones are lost within that same shifting desert, crying out to be found like distant voices, still lives, calling from the edge of the galaxy.</p><p>Elegantly, astutely, elegiacally, Guzmán pulls these threads (and others) together, proving that past and present collide on a cosmic level, and reminding us that whoever does not know history is condemned to repeat it. A stunningly moving and brilliantly eye-opening work that perfectly demonstrates the transformative power of the moving image, <em>Nostalgia for the Light</em> is a must-see film that ranks alongside the documentaries of Werner Herzog in its profound insight into the human condition. Superb.</p><p>Less philosophically earth-shattering but equally impressive in its attention to visual detail, Aardman's splendidly monikered <strong>The Pirates! In an</strong> <strong>Adventure With Scientists!</strong> (2012, Sony, U) finds Bristol's finest once again packing the screen with the kind of blink-and-you'll-miss-them treasures that demand repeat viewing. Despite being less laugh-out-loud funny than some of their previous outings, this will nevertheless paint a lasting smile on the faces of viewers of all ages. A merry mash-up of swashbuckling puns, dead-dodo Darwinian theory and (in its final stages) explosive steam-punk Victoriana, this rollicking stop-motion romp puts the digimated dreariness of most Hollywood animations in the shade. Extensive extras include dress-up games and enjoyable feature commentary. Oh, and it goes without saying that it all looks brighter, clearer and better in good old glasses-free 2D; the format of the future!</p><p>While his refusal to toe anything even vaguely resembling the mainstream narrative line may be admirable, Hungarian director Béla Tarr's previous movies have sometimes proved unendurably patience-testing; watching <em>The Man from London</em> at the Cannes film festival, I resorted to jabbing my thumbnail repeatedly into my thigh in order to stave off sleep. A relief, then, to report that <strong>The Turin Horse </strong>(2011, Artificial Eye, 15) positively flies by – at least by Tarr's exacting standards. Inspired by Nietzsche's near-mythical encounter with a flogged and dying horse that sent him into an incurable depressive tailspin, this paints an end-of-days picture of a colourless world in which the well of life has run dry and there's a mighty storm coming. Composed of trademark extended single takes, each brimful of portent and foreboding, this hypnotically powerful vision about \"the heaviness of human existence\" is ironically the director's most accessible work to date. What a shame, as he recently announced, it's also <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/2012/may/26/bela-tarr-turin-horse\" title=\"\">his last</a>.</p><p>Having jerked the comedy appendage of <em>American Pie</em> dry with a series of increasingly unrewarding sequels, the once priapic teens of this post-<a href=\"http://uk.imdb.com/title/tt0084522/\" title=\"\"><em>Porky's</em></a> money-spinner whip the wrinkled old fella out once again for <strong>American Pie: Reunion</strong> (2012, Universal, 15). While it would be tempting to imagine that with age comes knowledge, what's most notable about this is just how little anything has moved on – and just how unemployed some of these \"rising stars\" have been. Thus we open with an extended masturbation set piece, move to Stifler shitting in someone's lunchbox and thence to Jim's dad causing the pages of his son's porn mags to stick together. Overall it's like some Hits on 45 compilation mega-mix of all the familiar riffs from the previous movies, once spunky, now tired and flaccid.</p><p>At the very opposite end of the spectrum, Mia Hansen-Løve's <strong>Goodbye First Love</strong> (2011, Artificial Eye, 15)  explores the paradox of youthful infatuation revisited, as 19-year-old Sullivan abandons his Parisian soulmate Camille to travel through South America, only for their paths to cross several years later, by which point both of their lives have become irrevocably changed. Boasting a standout performance by Lola Créton, so arresting in Catherine&nbsp;Breillat's <em>Bluebeard</em>, this pitches its semi-autobiographical camp&nbsp;in a dreamy midway point between the unaffected&nbsp;innocence of <em>Gregory's Girl</em> and the unblinking harshness of <em>9 Songs</em>, building affectingly upon the&nbsp;promise of Hansen-Løve's <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/2010/mar/07/philip-french-father-of-my-children\" title=\"\"><em>Father of my Children</em></a>.</p><p>Just time for some head-cracking action from Jason Statham in <strong>Safe</strong> (2012, Momentum, 15), in which everyone's favourite beefcake  attempts to protect a young girl &nbsp;from vile thugs in the US of A. Not the Stath's finest work, perhaps, but further proof of a broadening palette from one of exploitation cinema's&nbsp; most level-headed stalwarts.</p>","headline":"Mark Kermode's DVD round-up","trailText":"The stunning Nostalgia for the Light explores Chileans' search for murdered relatives, while director Béla Tarr signs off in style, writes <strong>Mark Kermode</strong>","newspaperPageNumber":"24","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Observer","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Observer/Pix/pictures/2012/9/5/1346853886059/Nostalgia-For-The-Light-K-005.jpg","wordcount":"774","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"395691175","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"6626534","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Mark Kermode","newspaperEditionDate":"2012-09-09T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"1797093","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2012-09-30T13:53:00Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2012/sep/09/nostalgia-for-light-turin-dvd","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/film/2012/sep/09/nostalgia-for-light-turin-dvd","tags":[{"id":"film/series/mark-kermode-dvd-round-up","webTitle":"Mark Kermode's DVD round-up","description":"Mark Kermode reviews the latest DVD releases","type":"series","sectionId":"film","sectionName":"Film","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/series/mark-kermode-dvd-round-up","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/film/series/mark-kermode-dvd-round-up","references":[]},{"id":"film/documentary","webTitle":"Documentary","type":"keyword","sectionId":"film","sectionName":"Film","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/documentary","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/film/documentary","references":[]},{"id":"film/animation","webTitle":"Animation","type":"keyword","sectionId":"film","sectionName":"Film","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/animation","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/film/animation","references":[]},{"id":"film/drama","webTitle":"Drama","type":"keyword","sectionId":"film","sectionName":"Film","webUrl":"http://www.the