uby Sparks; Room 237; Untouchable; Chained; Pusher","hasStoryPackage":"false","lastModified":"2014-05-21T15:01:20Z","body":"<p>A quasi-apocalyptic fable filmed amid the aftermath of hurricane Katrina, Benh Zeitlin's extraordinary <a href=\"http://www.amazon.co.uk/Beasts-Southern-Wild-Quvenzhan%C3%A9-Wallis/dp/B009HU9V0E/ref=sr_1_1?s=dvd&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1360157730&amp;sr=1-1\" title=\"\"><strong>Beasts of the Southern Wild</strong></a> (2012, StudioCanal, 12) follows the changing fortunes of a vibrant young girl and her sickly father as they face an uncertain future in the fictional bayou community of the Bathtub. Based on Lucy Alibar's play <em>Juicy and Delicious</em>, Zeitlin's unexpected awards contender boasts rising waters, mythical creatures and superbly believable characters. As Hushpuppy, Quvenzhané Wallis is the youngest nominee to compete in Oscar's best actress category, while Dwight Henry had to be dragged away from his day job running a local bakery to star in the movie; both are mesmerising. The decision to shoot on 16mm rather than digital pays splendid visual dividends, lending richly colourful texture to the proceedings as they slip effortlessly between grainy realism and fantasy. A challenging treat for viewers of all ages, this really is remarkable fare. Extras include film-maker commentary and deleted scenes, along with Zeitlin's award-winning 2008 short <em>Glory at Sea</em>.</p><p>Depending upon your point of view, you can read screenwriter and star Zoe Kazan's <a href=\"http://www.amazon.co.uk/Ruby-Sparks-DVD-Paul-Dano/dp/B008OHD2BU/ref=sr_1_1?s=dvd&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1360151297&amp;sr=1-1\" title=\"\"><strong>Ruby Sparks</strong></a><strong> </strong>(2012, Fox, 15) as either an intriguing treatise about a woman being forced to conform to a twisted male ideal or just a superannuated retelling of the teen-boy fantasy <em>Weird Science</em> with books. Paul Dano plays the blocked Salingeresque writer who accidentally conjures his dream girl (Kazan) from his typewriter and then can't resist the temptation to edit and rewrite her, thus destroying the very thing he loved. Swerving between irksomely quirky comedy and semi-Frankensteinian horror (one scene invokes demonic possession), this is uneven work that never satisfactorily resolves its fantastical plot problems, but Kazan's role as author of her own destiny provides for unexpected depths and subtextual intrigue.</p><p>Like poor old author Jack Torrance, who spends too much time alone with his thoughts and winds up chasing himself around a maze in <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/2012/nov/04/the-shining-stanley-kubrick-review\" title=\"\"><em>The Shining</em></a>, film theory goes quietly mad in <a href=\"http://www.amazon.co.uk/Room-237-DVD-Rodney-Ascher/dp/B009WQR7UO/ref=sr_1_1?s=dvd&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1360152388&amp;sr=1-1\" title=\"\"><strong>Room 237</strong></a><strong> </strong>(2012, Metrodome, 15), in which obsessive fans search for the meaning of life in Kubrick's adaptation of Stephen King's chiller. As scenes from the movie are watched, replayed, freeze-framed, flipped, reversed, overlaid, superimposed and generally dismantled on screen, we hear fans, academics and madmen alike explaining that the film is variously about the Holocaust (maybe), native American genocide (arguably), sexual repression (possibly), numerology (conceivably), and how the director faked footage of the moon landings (no, sorry, you lost me there… ).</p><p>It's bizarrely fascinating, exhilarating and exasperating stuff in which every continuity error becomes a super-signifier and nothing is accidental – ever. What Kubrick actually \"meant\" remains a mystery, but this dazzling documentary stands as proof that the very best movies give to you whatever you bring to them, even if you're a lunatic.</p><p>A strong contender for the foreign language film statuette at this evening's Baftas, <a href=\"http://www.amazon.co.uk/Untouchable-DVD-Fran%C3%A7ois-Cluzet/dp/B00A6VGLJM/ref=sr_1_1?s=dvd&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1360152801&amp;sr=1-1\" title=\"\"><strong>Untouchable</strong></a> (2011, Entertainment, 15) is a crowd-pleasing souffle of a movie about an unlikely friendship between a rich Parisian quadriplegic and his streetwise assistant. Inspired by the true story of an Algerian ex-con (whose nationality is here transposed) and his aristocratic employer turned friend, this benefits from the palpable chemistry between François Cluzet and Omar Sy, whose interplay zings with wit, warmth and&nbsp;humour. For those untroubled by the lack of rough edges, this is proper feel-good fare – jubilant, funny and often moving.</p><p>After the boggy catastrophe of <em>Boxing Helena</em> and the sprightly career resurrection of <a href=\"http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0409345/?ref_=fn_al_tt_3\" title=\"\"><em>Surveillance</em></a>, Jennifer Lynch slips into dreary horror plodathon mode for<strong> </strong><a href=\"http://www.amazon.co.uk/Chained-DVD-Vincent-D-Onofrio/dp/B00A9YBVMS/ref=sr_1_1?s=dvd&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1360153523&amp;sr=1-1\" title=\"\"><strong>Chained</strong></a> (2012, Anchor Bay, 18), a nasty, derivative psycho-schlocker that wastes a committed central performance by Vincent D'Onofrio as a serial killer with a captive child. While Markus Schleinzer's <a href=\"http://www.imdb.com/title/tt1906426/\" title=\"\"><em>Michael</em></a> presented a terrifyingly deadpan account of a comparable scenario, this merely gestures toward character insight before insulting its audience with a dumbo WTF? plot twist that will have you groaning in pain. Not good.</p><p>Nicolas Winding Refn directed three episodes of his rent-paying <a href=\"http://www.amazon.co.uk/Pusher-Trilogy-DVD-Mads-Mikkelsen/dp/B000FH8TZ6/ref=sr_1_1?s=dvd&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1360153983&amp;sr=1-1\" title=\"\"><em>Pusher</em></a> series before his mainstream ship finally came in with <em>Drive</em>. Money remains the driving force behind the English-language version of <a href=\"http://www.amazon.co.uk/Pusher-DVD-Richard-Coyle/dp/B009YUYZY4/ref=sr_1_4?s=dvd&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1360153983&amp;sr=1-4\" title=\"\"><strong>Pusher</strong></a> (2012, Vertigo, 18), a stylish but essentially redundant rehash of Refn's original, which moves the action from Copenhagen to London while retaining&nbsp;enigmatic villain Zlatko Buric. The result is flashier but emptier than its predecessor.</p>","headline":"Mark Kermode's DVD round-up","trailText":"<p>A magical fable set in the Louisiana bayou in the aftermath of hurricane Katrina is a treat for viewers of all ages, writes <strong>Mark Kermode</strong></p>","newspaperPageNumber":"26","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Observer","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/guardian/About/General/2013/2/6/1360158128682/Quvenzhan--Wallis-in-Beas-005.jpg","wordcount":"701","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"403622665","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"7216423","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Mark Kermode","newspaperEditionDate":"2013-02-10T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"1863780","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2013-03-03T00:01:00Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/feb/10/beasts-southern-wild-dvd-kermode","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/film/2013/feb/10/beasts-southern-wild-dvd-kermode","tags":[{"id":"film/series/mark-kermode-dvd-round-up","webTitle":"Mark Kermode's DVD round-up","description":"Mark Kermode reviews the latest DVD releases","type":"series","sectionId":"film","sectionName":"Film","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/series/mark-kermode-dvd-round-up","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/film/series/mark-kermode-dvd-round-up","references":[]},{"id":"film/dvdreviews","webTitle":"DVD and video reviews","type":"keyword","sectionId":"film","sectionName":"Film","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/dvdreviews","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.gu